ElasticPotentialEnergy

The Elastic Potential Energy of an Ideal Spring

The potential energy stored in a spring is proportional to the square of the displacement of the spring from its equilibrium position.

E = \frac{1}{2} k x^{2}

where:

E [var. scal. ElasticPotentialEnergy, M L^{2} T^{-2}, J] is the elastic potential energy stored in the spring
k [const. scal. SpringConstant, M T^{-2}, N m^{-1}] is the spring constant of the spring
x [var. scal. Displacement, L, m] is the displacement of the spring from its equilibrium position

